<subSubSection pageId="70" pageNumber="349" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="70.[732,1327,298,721]" pageId="70" pageNumber="349">
<taxonomicName box="[733,997,298,327]" class="Mammalia" family="Cricetidae" genus="Microtus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Rodentia" pageId="70" pageNumber="349" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="nebrodensis">Microtus nebrodensis</taxonomicName>
is in subgenus Terricola and savi species group. It was separated from 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Selys-Longchamps" authorityYear="1838" box="[811,919,372,405]" class="Mammalia" family="Cricetidae" genus="Pitymys" kingdom="Animalia" order="Rodentia" pageId="70" pageNumber="349" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="savii">M. savii</taxonomicName>
recently based on molecular evidence. As revealed from topology of phylogenetic tree, M. 
<taxonomicName box="[1063,1204,451,484]" class="Mammalia" family="Cricetidae" genus="Microtus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Rodentia" pageId="70" pageNumber="349" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="nebrodensis">nebrodensis</taxonomicName>
is sister species to the lineage containing 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Selys-Longchamps" authorityYear="1838" box="[1203,1263,491,524]" class="Mammalia" family="Cricetidae" genus="Pitymys" kingdom="Animalia" order="Rodentia" pageId="70" pageNumber="349" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="savii">savii</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Lehmann" authorityYear="1961" box="[734,889,530,563]" class="Mammalia" family="Cricetidae" genus="Microtus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Rodentia" pageId="70" pageNumber="349" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="brachycercus">brachycercus</taxonomicName>
. Monotypic.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection box="[732,1167,570,603]" pageId="70" pageNumber="349" type="distribution">
<caption ID-DOI="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6760665" ID-Zenodo-Dep="6760665" box="[732,1167,570,603]" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6760665/files/figure.png" inLine="true" pageId="70" pageNumber="349" startId="70.[732,904,570,603]" targetBox="[117,709,302,716]" targetPageId="70">
<paragraph blockId="70.[732,1327,298,721]" box="[732,1167,570,603]" pageId="70" pageNumber="349">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[732,908,570,603]" pageId="70" pageNumber="349">Distribution.</emphasis>
Endemic to Sicily.
</paragraph>
</caption>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="70" pageNumber="349" type="description">
<paragraph blockId="70.[732,1327,298,721]" lastBlockId="70.[118,1327,732,1273]" pageId="70" pageNumber="349">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[732,975,609,642]" pageId="70" pageNumber="349">Descriptive notes.</emphasis>
Head-body 96-104 mm, tail 16-26 mm; weight 18-5-21-5 g. The Sicilian Pine Vole is, on average, larger than Savi’s Pine Vole (
<taxonomicName authorityName="Selys-Longchamps" authorityYear="1838" box="[352,458,732,761]" class="Mammalia" family="Cricetidae" genus="Pitymys" kingdom="Animalia" order="Rodentia" pageId="70" pageNumber="349" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="savii">M. savii</taxonomicName>
) or the Calabria Pine Vole (M. brachicercus), but otherwise similar to them. Females have two pairs of inguinal nipples and a pair of pectoral ones (six nipples in total). The Sicilian Pine Vole has lower number of vertebrae (45 total) than Savi’s Pine Vole (47). Pelage of the Sicilian Pine Vole is buffy brown on back and silver and shaded yellowish on belly. Skull and dental pattern do not deviate from those of Savi’s Pine Vole.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection box="[120,1024,964,997]" pageId="70" pageNumber="349" type="biology_ecology">
<paragraph blockId="70.[118,1327,732,1273]" box="[120,1024,964,997]" pageId="70" pageNumber="349">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[120,231,964,997]" pageId="70" pageNumber="349">Habitat.</emphasis>
The Sicilian Pine Vole lives at elevations of 175-1700 m.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
